[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(8) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Zadok the priest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (son of Ahitub) was the representative of the family of Eleazar, elder son of Aaron, as Abiathar of the family of Ithamar, the younger son (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 24:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). As a “young man of valour,” under “Jehoiada, leader of the Aaronites,” he joined David at Hebron with 3,700 men (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 12:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and had been left in charge of the Tabernacle at Gibeon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 16:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") after the removal of the Ark to Jerusalem. On his relation to Abiathar, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 2:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Benaiah, the son of “Jehoiada, a chief priest,” and therefore of Levitical origin. (See 2Samuel 8:18; 2Samuel 23:20-23; 1Chronicles 27:5-6.) His rank is given in 2Samuel 23:23, as intermediate between the “three mighty men” and “the thirty,” and in 1Chronicles 27:5, as “the third captain of the host for the third month”; but his command of the bodyguard gave him special importance, second only to that of Joab (2Samuel 20:23), and perhaps of even greater importance for immediate action. (It is notable that there is no mention of Abishai, who is named as prior to Benaiah among “the mighty men” in 2Samuel 23:18-22. It may be inferred that he was dead; otherwise he could hardly have been omitted here.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Benaiah",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", the son of “Jehoiada, a chief priest,” and therefore of Levitical origin. (See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 8:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:20-23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 27:5-6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) His rank is given in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", as intermediate between the “three mighty men” and “the thirty,” and in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 27:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", as “the third captain of the host for the third month”; but his command of the bodyguard gave him special importance, second only to that of Joab (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 20:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and perhaps of even greater importance for immediate action. (It is notable that there is no mention of Abishai, who is named as prior to Benaiah among “the mighty men” in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:18-22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". It may be inferred that he was dead; otherwise he could hardly have been omitted here.)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Nathan the prophet.—See 2Samuel 7:2; 2Samuel 12:1; 2Samuel 12:25. In the whole chapter he appears rather as a chief officer and counsellor of David, than in the loftier aspect of the prophetic character. He was also the royal chronicler of the reigns of David and Solomon (1Chronicles 29:29; 2Chronicles 9:29).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Nathan the prophet",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".—See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 7:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 12:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 12:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". In the whole chapter he appears rather as a chief officer and counsellor of David, than in the loftier aspect of the prophetic character. He was also the royal chronicler of the reigns of David and Solomon (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:29",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 9:29",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Shimei, and Rei.—Ewald conjectures that these were two brothers of David, called Shimma and Raddai in 1Chronicles 2:13-14. These, however, being older than David, would now be in extreme old age. Of Rei, we have no mention elsewhere; but there is a Shimei (in 1Kings 4:18), a high officer of Solomon; a “Shimea,” brother of Solomon (in 1Chronicles 3:5), and a “Shammah,” one of the “mighty men” (in 2Samuel 23:11).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Shimei, and Rei",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".—Ewald conjectures that these were two brothers of David, called Shimma and Raddai in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 2:13-14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". These, however, being older than David, would now be in extreme old age. Of Rei, we have no mention elsewhere; but there is a Shimei (in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 4:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), a high officer of Solomon; a “Shimea,” brother of Solomon (in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 3:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and a “Shammah,” one of the “mighty men” (in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The mighty men.—See 2Samuel 23:8-39. The name Gibbôrim is a technical name, and is thought to designate a picked body of troops, the standing nucleus of the armies of Israel. It is commonly inferred that they were the successors of the six hundred men of David’s band during his life of wandering and exile, and that “the three” and “the thirty” (2 Samuel 23) were their officers. They are mentioned as attached to the person of David in 2Samuel 10:7; 2Samuel 16:6, 2Sa_20:7.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The mighty men",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".—See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 23:8-39",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The name ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Gibbôrim",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is a technical name, and is thought to designate a picked body of troops, the standing nucleus of the armies of Israel. It is commonly inferred that they were the successors of the six hundred men of David’s band during his life of wandering and exile, and that “the three” and “the thirty” (2 Samuel 23) were their officers. They are mentioned as attached to the person of David in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 10:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 16:6, 2Sa_20:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:8-10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 1:8-10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The mighty men were not with Adonijah — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, those named 2 Samuel 23., and the guards, who had served under David so long, and had done such mighty acts in his reign and under his conduct. Adonijah had no hope of drawing them to his party, and therefore did not confer with them as he did with Joab and Abiathar. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And called all his brethren and all the men of Judah — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Except those mentioned ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and again excepted, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But all the rest of the family of David, and the principal persons of the tribe of Judah, with the high-priest and captain of the host, being present, there seemed to be nothing wanting to the making of him king, but only his anointing. For this appears to have been a federal feast, in which they swore allegiance to Adonijah. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But Nathan the prophet, and Benaiah, &c., he called not — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Because he knew they favoured Solomon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:5-10 Indulgent parents are often chastised with disobedient children, who are anxious to possess their estates. No worldly wisdom, nor experience, nor sacredness of character, can insure the continuance in any former course of those who remain under the power of self-love. But we may well wonder by what arts Joab and Abiathar could be drawn aside.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "There is some difficulty in understanding how Zadok and Abiathar came to be both \"priests\" at this time, and in what relation they stood to one another. The best explanation seems to be that Abiathar was the real high priest, and officiated at the sanctuary containing the ark of the covenant in Zion, while Zadok performed the offices of chief priest at the tabernacle of Witness at Gibeon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 16:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For Benaiah, see 2 Samuel 8:18; 2 Samuel 20:23; 2 Samuel 23:20-21. For Nathan, see 2 Samuel 7:2-3, 2 Samuel 7:17; 2 Samuel 12:1-15, 2 Samuel 12:25. As privy to all David's plans 1 Kings 1:24, he had no doubt fully approved the order of succession which the king was known to intend.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "For Benaiah, see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 20:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 23:20-21",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". For Nathan, see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 7:2-3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 7:17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 12:1-15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 12:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". As privy to all David's plans ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 1:24",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", he had no doubt fully approved the order of succession which the king was known to intend.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Shimei and Rei - Shimei and Rei are perhaps David's two brothers, Shimma and Raddai 1 Chronicles 2:13-14.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Shimei and Rei - Shimei and Rei are perhaps David's two brothers, Shimma and Raddai ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Chronicles 2:13-14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Mighty men - Probably the company of 600, originally formed during David's early wanderings 1 Samuel 25:13; 1 Samuel 27:2, and afterward maintained as the most essential element of his standing army. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Mighty men - Probably the company of 600, originally formed during David's early wanderings ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Samuel 25:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Samuel 27:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and afterward maintained as the most essential element of his standing army. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
