  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But Zadok the priest,.... Who bid fair to be the high priest on Solomon's coming to the throne as he was: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada; who was near David's person, and over his bodyguards, the Cherethites and Pelethites: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and Nathan the prophet; a very great intimate of David's, and his seer, whom he consulted on all occasions: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and Shimei; who, according to Abarbinel, was Shimei the son of Gera, who had cursed David, and was afraid of entering into the conspiracy, lest he should be involved in trouble again: though some think this may be that Shimei, one of Solomon's twelve officers, as after constituted, 1 Kings 4:18; ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "and Shimei; who, according to Abarbinel, was Shimei the son of Gera, who had cursed David, and was afraid of entering into the conspiracy, lest he should be involved in trouble again: though some think this may be that Shimei, one of Solomon's twelve officers, as after constituted, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Kings 4:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and Rei; whom the same writer takes to be Hushai the Archite, David's friend: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and the mighty men which belonged to David; that were about his person, his guards, the Cherethites and Pelethites: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "were not with Adonijah; they did not join him, and indeed were not invited by him. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "were not with Adonijah; they did not join him, and indeed were not invited by him. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "But Zadok the priest, and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada, and Nathan the prophet, and Shimei, and Rei, and the mighty men which belonged to David, were not with Adonijah.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But Zadok the priest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] He was the son of Ahitub, and descended from Eleazar, the son of Aaron. He joined David after the death of Saul, and there were thus two priests, perhaps one being highpriest and the other second priest, through the whole of David’s reign. Zadok’s duties appear (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 16:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to have been at the Tabernacle in Gibeon, and Abiathar had charge of the ark in Jerusalem. But in consequence of the events described in this chapter Abiathar was thrust out of his office and banished to Anathoth, and Zadok became the sole highpriest.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Benaiah the son of Jehoiada",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This man, though of the tribe of Levi, became captain of David’s body-guard of Cherethites and Pelethites (see below on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and was made, when Joab was dead, commander in chief of Solomon’s army.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Nathan the prophet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] He was prominent in David’s reign, giving the king advice concerning the building of the Temple, bringing God’s rebuke after David’s adultery and the message of forgiveness when he had repented. He appears also in connexion with the birth of Solomon and now as the adviser and helper of Bath-sheba. After Solomon was proclaimed king we hear no more of Nathan.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and Shimei",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] There is a person so called mentioned afterwards as one of the twelve officers who provided victuals for king Solomon and his household. But whether that be the Shimei here mentioned there is no means of deciding. It was conjectured by Ewald that it was another way of writing the name of Shimeah, David’s brother.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and Rei",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rei is not mentioned elsewhere, and there is nothing to guide us to any opinion concerning his identity. Several conjectures have been made, but none that deserves much attention.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the mighty",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " men ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "which",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " belonged ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to David",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Of these champions a list is given ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:8-39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with which may be compared ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 11:10-47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But Zadok the priest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is generally said to be difficult to explain \"how Zadok and Abiathar came  both to be \"priests at this time.\" Rawlinson, who adds that \"the best explanation is that Abiathar was the real high priest,\" officiating in Zion, while Zadok acted as chief priest at the tabernacle at Gibeon. (Bahr, by a strange oversight, assigns to Zadok the care of the ark on Mount Zion, whereas ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 16:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", distinctly connects his ministry with the tabernacle of witness at Gibeon.) But the precedence (see on ver. 7) generally assigned to Zadok is hardly consistent with the idea that Abiathar was \"the real high priest.\" The fact is that a duality of high priests, associated, apparently, on pretty equal terms, was not unknown in Jewish history. The cases of Eleazer and Ithamar, Hophni and Phinehas, Annas and Caiaphas, will occur to all. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", speaks of \"the chief priest\" and \"the second priest;\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 31:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of the \"chief priest of the house of Zadok.\" And a dual priesthood would be the more necessary in David's days, because of the two sanctuaries, Zion and Gibeon. We find, however, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that Zadok was already priest at the time of the bringing up of the ark. And the true explanation, no doubt, is that Zadok had succeeded some member of his family, in all probability Jehoiada, called in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 12:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"the leader of Aaron\" (Hebrews), who had certainly been high priest in the time of Saul (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and who would hardly be degraded when, with 3700 followers, he joined David at Hebron. On his decease, or cession of orifice, Zadok, who had joined at the same time with a large contingent,was associated with Abiathar in the priest's office. This dual arrangement, consequently, was the result of David's having taken over a high priest from Saul, together with the kingdom, when he had Abiathar as priest already,] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jehoiada the high priest (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Benaiah was consequently a Levite, and of the family of Aaron; set, however, by David, because of his prowess (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:20, 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 11:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") over the bodyguard (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 18:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Probably he was a near relative of Zadok.], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and Nathan the prophet",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [a Jewish tradition makes Nathan the eighth son of Jesse. He comes before us ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 7:2, 3, 17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:1-12, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and Shimei",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [by Ewald identified with Shammah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 16:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or Shimeah, David's brother (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 13:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Others suppose him to be the Shimei of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But see note on chap. 2:8. Josephus calls Shimei (not Rei, as Bahr states) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὁ Δαυίδου φίλος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and Rei",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [this name occurs here only. Ewald would identify him with Raddai (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "),  another brother of David, but on very slender grounds], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and the mighty men",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [or heroes. Gesen. \"chiefs.\" Not the 600 men who formed David's band in his wanderings (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 25:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 27:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") (Rawlinson), but the 30 (or 37) to whom this name of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Gibborim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is expressly given, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 11:15, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 10:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Hebrews] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "which belonged to David",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [same expression as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "were not with Adonijah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 1 Kings 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If Adonijah had powerful supporters in Joab the commander-in-chief and the high priest Abiathar, the rest of the leading officers of state, viz., Zadok the high priest (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), Benaiah, captain of the king's body-guard (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:20-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the prophet Nathan, Shimei (probably the son of Elah mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and Rei (unknown), and the Gibborim of David (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), were not with him.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]